course_title: The History Workshop - History of Creativity
description: Introduction to the "historian's craft." Reconstructing the past using primary documents such as diaries, letters, memoirs, and declassified government papers. Methods of historical research and reasoning through individual projects. Offered on a graded basis only. [3] (SBS)
notes:
This class is not intended for first year students
         
            
            Creativity is a deceptively elusive concept, at once rare and seemingly everywhere. Where does it come from, and can it be cultivated? Is it a hollow notion we simply project to impress potential employers, or is it a valuable civic ideal? Could it be the key to the good life? And in the age of AI, is it an activity that we can (or should) share with machines? This upper-level history seminar explores historical discourse on the concept of creativity in the modern US since 1870 - in fields as disparate as music, science, the arts, industry, and business. Students will read a variety of primary sources exploring creativity since the late 19th-century. Throughout the course, students will design and develop their own research projects related to the history of creativity.

course_title: The History Workshop - History from Scraps

course_title: The History Workshop - Property, Law and the State
description: Introduction to the "historian's craft." Reconstructing the past using primary documents such as diaries, letters, memoirs, and declassified government papers. Methods of historical research and reasoning through individual projects. Offered on a graded basis only. [3] (SBS)
notes:
This class is not intended for first year students
         
            
            The subject of this course is a central transformation in the notion of property in Western thought and society. Namely, how individual property became an exclusive and exclusionary subjective right that is at the same time fundamental to the legitimacy of the state. The course examines problems the transformation of concepts and values, the relationship between social structures and human action, and the problem of individual agency (whether of men or women). The course will introduce you to scholarship that operates at the intersection of the history of ideas, political, legal, and social history. This course is designed to introduce you to history, historiography, and historical methods, especially those employed in the intellectual history. We will look at how historians work, how they define history, as well as a variety of approaches to historical writing. Most importantly, we will work to develop your own research and writing skills.

description: Introduction to the "historian's craft." Reconstructing the past using primary documents such as diaries, letters, memoirs, and declassified government papers. Methods of historical research and reasoning through individual projects. Offered on a graded basis only. [3] (SBS)
notes:
Black Lives Matter, the Tea Party, revolutionaries, reformists, sit-ins, signature drives, and hashtags--how can we explain these kinds of historical events that we call "social movements"? When, why, and how to people choose collective action as an avenue for social change? To answer these questions together, we'll first examine the craft of the historian. We'll study the basics of historical writing, research, and historiography, stopping along the way to borrow some theory and research methods from the sociology of collective action. Using this toolkit, students will conclude the course by writing their own original research essay analyzing a historical social movement. Students in this course will not just learn to be historians, but to also be historical sociologists, social movement scholars, and good writers.
         
            
            This class is not intended for first year students

description: Introduction to the "historian's craft." Reconstructing the past using primary documents such as diaries, letters, memoirs, and declassified government papers. Methods of historical research and reasoning through individual projects. Offered on a graded basis only. [3] (SBS)
notes: This class is not intended for first year students This seminar broaches the study of sports historically. Readings and short assignments will initially center on methodology, with the first third of the semester geared towards an analysis of different approaches and questions that are driving the best scholarship. We will also reflect on how the writing about sports oftentimes entails writing for audiences beyond academia, and its implications for the writing process. We will discuss various kinds of sources, including, biographies and autobiographies, film and documentaries, oral history, and print and TV media. The topics explored range from immigration and politics, to gender and sexuality, and also nationalism and empire. Most baseline readings will draw from Latin American and Latino histories, but you may ultimately write papers on places and contexts of your choosing.

course_title: The History Workshop - Empire and Sovereignty
description: Introduction to the "historian's craft." Reconstructing the past using primary documents such as diaries, letters, memoirs, and declassified government papers. Methods of historical research and reasoning through individual projects. Offered on a graded basis only. [3] (SBS)
notes:
This class is not intended for first year students.
         
            
            In order to understand modern international politics, we need to comprehend the role of empire in structuring relationships of global power throughout history. This course will introduce students to the practice of historical research and writing while thinking through the various forms that empire has taken over time and how imperial powers conceptualized sovereignty. From the Roman Empire to early modern European imperialism in the Atlantic World and Indian Ocean World, to contests for imperial control in nineteenth-century Africa and the interwar Middle East, the Soviet Union, and twenty-first century corporations, we will examine how empires across history have been legally constituted and how imperial powers sought to legally justify their claims to sovereignty. Building on this study, students will spend the second half of the semester developing their own independent research projects related to empire and sovereignty. In the process, students will leave the course with the ability to identify and engage with scholarly literature, locate and analyze primary sources, and craft historical arguments.

course_title: Introduction to Law and the Legal System
description: This course will introduce students to the study of American law. It is a required course designed to give students the knowledge and skills that will prepare them for the other courses that contribute to a Minor in Legal Studies, as well as applying to and succeeding in law school. What are the institutions (such as the legislature and the courts) and sources of law (such as statutes and judicial decisions) that comprise the American legal system? How do you read a judicial decision and understand how law develops over time? How do you "think like a lawyer"? This course may focus on a particular subject matter, such as administrative law or negotiations, to introduce the basic concepts. [3]

course_title: Service Learning in the Biomedical Sciences
requirements: Students must be enrolled in the MS Program in the Biomedical Sciences.
description: This course structures opportunities for students in the MS Program in the Biomedical Sciences to participate in service/learning experiences in the Nashville area. Students will arrange activities that complement medical school applications. The course will be one credit hour, offered every semester. At the end of each semester, students will write a paper describing their experiences. [1]

course_title: Ethical Principles and Practices for Biostatisticians
description: This reading and discussion-based course is based on the American Statistical Association's Ethical Guidelines for Statistical Practice. Topics include professional integrity and accountability, integrity of data and methods, responsibilities to science/public/funder/client, responsibilities to research subjects, responsibilities to research team colleagues, responsibilities to other statisticians or statistics practitioners, responsibilities regarding allegations of misconduct, and responsibilities of employers, including organizations, individuals, attorneys, or other clients employing statistical practitioners. Prerequisites: None. Fall [0]. Greevy.

This course will provide students with knowledge and understanding of financial literacy and essential money management skills. This course will introduce essential interpersonal skills, such as active listening, effective communication, and personal accountability. Additionally, this course will introduce and explore topics in independent living including personal home safety, home management, and community mapping. Students will build awareness and skills in budgeting, credit management, and financial safety. These course goals will be achieved through integrated approaches such as service learning, critical and reflective journaling, lecture, discussion, and community-based immersion experiences. [3]

course_title: Practicum in the Teaching of Religion, Part I
description: This two-semester (no credit) course for first year PhD students in the GDR. This course will be led by a GDR faculty member and will include various faculty members presenting on selected topics, as scheduled in the syllabus. The focus will be on training in the basics of teaching in a university setting. Topics include syllabus preparation and course design, inclusivity in the classroom, grading, lecturing, discussion leadership, technologies in teaching, teaching documentation (teaching statements, etc.), grant design and writing. In addition, discussion of mentoring in the GDR, using the GDR mentoring policy as a guide, planning a strategy for professional development training catered to each student's needs and expectations. This plan includes specific Center for Teaching certificates that the student is expected to complete, and other training offered in the CFT. [0]
